equation_narrative.headline: Hydrophobic representation shifts to polar, but alanine wins over glutamate
equation_narrative.story: The model assembles a mixed biochemical context at position 24, reading 6 structural contacts and minimal co-evolutionary signal. Early layers (L1-9) build a hydrophobic-leaning representation, with leucine peaking at 32% in the logit lens at L9, reflecting local hydrophobic neighbors. Mid-layers (L10-23) shift toward polar character as serine rises to 36% at L24, driven by attention to local polar residues. In the decision phase (L24-33), alanine surges from 12% to 39%, powered by MLP neurons that favor small, flexible residues, ultimately defeating the correct answer glutamate (which ranks 10th at 2.4%).

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 gather structural and local sequence context. Six structural contacts are read, creating an initially hydrophobic representation: leucine peaks at 32% at L9 (F9:5728, F9:1281 with 61.96 and 57.08 projections), consistent with buried hydrophobic neighbors. Attention heads at L10 (3.36 total_delta toward E) and L12 (head 9 with 1.555 projection) read local sequence, introducing polar character. By L18, the representation shifts: serine rises to 14.5% and alanine emerges at 14.6%, reflecting mixed hydrophobic-polar context. Minimal co-evolutionary signal (only 1 coevolving position) means the model relies heavily on local chemistry. By L23, the representation is ambiguous—serine leads at 23.6%, but alanine (12.1%), leucine (12.3%), and polar residues all remain viable.
perception_phase.context_character: Mixed hydrophobic-polar local environment with 6 structural contacts. Early hydrophobic bias (leucine, valine) gives way to polar character (serine, threonine) by mid-layers, suggesting a flexible position at a hydrophobic-polar interface with minimal evolutionary constraint.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 6 residues within 8Å, read primarily at L9-10 via attention heads (F9:5728, F9:1281 with 61.96, 57.08 projections)
Co-evolutionary signal: only 1 coevolving position—minimal functional coupling
Local sequence attention: L10 head with 3.36 total_delta toward E; L12 head 9 with 1.555 projection reads nearby polar residues
L18 features: F18:6256 (15.98 proj), F18:5712 (12.21 proj) encode mixed structural context, shifting representation toward polar-flexible character

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes at L24-28. Serine briefly peaks at 36% at L24 (driven by F24:5080 with 21.34 projection), but alanine surges from 12% to 39% between L23 and L33. MLP neurons at L28-31 drive this shift: N28:4082 (0.697 proj for E) and N28:357 (0.578 proj for E) support glutamate, but are overwhelmed by alanine-favoring neurons like N31:2350 (0.48 proj for E, 0.455 for A). The model commits to alanine as a small, flexible residue compatible with the mixed context, underweighting the charged character that would favor glutamate.
decision_phase.transition: At L23-25, the representation transitions from context encoding to amino-acid-specific prediction. L24 features (F24:5080, F24:10131 with 21.34, 19.06 projections) are the first high-specificity prediction channels. Serine peaks at 36% at L24, but MLP neurons at L28 (total_answer_proj 5.26) begin casting decisive votes for alanine, marking the shift from 'what's here' to 'what should go here.'

candidates.narrative: Alanine emerges as a contender at L18 (14.6%) and wins decisively in the decision phase. At L28, MLP neurons shift strongly toward alanine: N28:1303 (0.511 proj for E, 0.556 for A) and the layer's net 5.26 total_answer_proj drive alanine from 12% to 32%. By L31, N31:2350 (0.48 proj for E, 0.455 for A) and attention at L33 (F33:9048 with 85.35 proj) lock in alanine at 39%. The model interprets the mixed hydrophobic-polar context as favoring a small, flexible residue over a charged one.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges L18, surges L28-31, peaks L33 at 39%
key_evidence: N28:1303 (0.556 proj for A, 0.511 for E) — favors small residues
L28 MLP total_answer_proj 5.26 — net push toward alanine

candidates.narrative: Glutamate is the correct answer but ranks 10th at only 2.4%. It receives support from MLP neurons throughout: N19:1792 (0.416 proj), N20:964 (0.411 proj), N28:4082 (0.697 proj), and N29:4262 (0.757 proj) all vote for E. However, this support is systematically erased by opposing neurons: N29:4973 (-0.9 proj), N30:362 (-1.024 proj), and N31:4495 (-0.876 proj) suppress glutamate in favor of alanine. The model underweights the charged character needed at this position.
key_evidence: N28:4082 (0.697 proj for E) — strongest E-specific neuron
N29:4262 (0.757 proj for E) — late support
N30:362 (-1.024 proj for E) — decisive eraser favoring hydrophobic residues

candidates.narrative: Serine leads the logit lens from L0 (22.6%) through L23 (23.6%), reflecting the polar character of the representation as the model reads local polar residues. This is NOT a prediction—it's a projection artifact showing that the accumulated features correlate with serine-like chemistry. Serine peaks at 36% at L24 (F24:5080 with 21.34 proj), but collapses to 10% by L29 as MLP neurons at L28 (-5.75 mlp_delta) and L30 (-5.54 mlp_delta) erase polar character in favor of alanine.
candidates.key_layers: Leads L0-L27, peaks L24 at 36%, collapses L28-29
key_evidence: F24:5080 (attn, 21.34 proj) — serine-specific feature at decision boundary
L28 MLP -5.75 delta away from S — decisive erasure

candidates.narrative: Leucine dominates the logit lens at L9 (32.3%), reflecting the hydrophobic character of the representation as the model reads buried structural contacts. F9:5728 (61.96 proj) and F9:1281 (57.08 proj) encode hydrophobic context, making leucine the strongest logit-lens projection. This does NOT mean the model predicts leucine—it means the features accumulated so far are hydrophobic-leaning. Leucine fades to 9.5% by L33 as the representation shifts toward polar and then small-flexible character.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks L9 at 32%, fades by L17 to 9.7%
key_evidence: L9 peak reflects representation character, not prediction

candidates.narrative: Asparagine is the runner-up at 11.7%, emerging late in the decision phase. It remains low (<4%) through L23, then surges at L29-33 as polar prediction channels activate. F33:326 (84.27 proj) and F33:2787 (82.07 proj) support asparagine as a polar alternative to alanine. However, it cannot overcome alanine's momentum from L28-31 MLP neurons that favor small, flexible residues over polar ones.
key_evidence: F33:2787 (attn, 82.07 proj) — polar alternative to alanine
Late surge insufficient to overcome alanine's L28-31 advantage

turning_points.description: The perception-to-decision transition occurs. At L23, the representation is ambiguous: serine 23.6%, alanine 12.1%, leucine 12.3%. At L24, the first high-specificity prediction channels activate (F24:5080 with 21.34 proj for serine), and serine briefly peaks at 36%. This marks the shift from 'encoding what's here' to 'predicting what should go here.' MLP neurons begin casting amino-acid-specific votes.

Alanine overtakes serine decisively. At L28, MLP neurons deliver a net 5.26 total_answer_proj, with N28:4082 (0.697 proj for E) and N28:1303 (0.556 proj for A) favoring small residues. Serine is erased by -5.75 MLP delta at L28 and -5.54 at L30. Alanine surges from 12% to 32% by L29. At L30-31, opposing neurons suppress glutamate (N30:362 with -1.024 proj, N31:4495 with -0.876 proj), cementing alanine's victory. This is the decisive moment where the model commits to alanine over the correct answer glutamate.

deep_dives.caption: L1 and L9 features encode the initial hydrophobic context from structural contacts. F9:5728 (61.96 proj) and F9:1281 (57.08 proj) reflect buried hydrophobic neighbors, creating the leucine-dominant logit lens at L9. This is representation character, not prediction.

deep_dives.caption: Attention heads at L10 (3.36 total_delta toward E) and L12 (head 9 with 1.555 projection) read structural contacts and local sequence. These heads shift the representation from hydrophobic (leucine) to polar (serine, threonine) by incorporating nearby polar residues.

deep_dives.label: Mid-layer representation shift (L18)
deep_dives.caption: L18 features (F18:6256 with 15.98 proj, F18:5712 with 12.21 proj) encode the transition from hydrophobic to mixed polar context. The logit lens shows serine and alanine emerging as co-leaders, reflecting the ambiguous biochemical environment.

deep_dives.label: Decision boundary features (L24)
deep_dives.caption: L24 is the perception-to-decision transition. F24:5080 (21.34 proj) and F24:10131 (19.06 proj) are the first high-specificity prediction channels, briefly favoring serine at 36%. These features mark the shift from context encoding to amino-acid-specific prediction.

deep_dives.label: MLP decision neurons (L28-31)
deep_dives.caption: L28-31 MLP neurons cast the decisive votes. N28:1303 (0.556 proj for A) and N28:4082 (0.697 proj for E) compete, but alanine-favoring neurons dominate. N30:362 (-1.024 proj) and N31:4495 (-0.876 proj) erase glutamate, while N31:2350 (0.455 proj for A) locks in alanine. This is where the model commits.

deep_dives.label: Final prediction channels (L30, L33)
deep_dives.caption: L30 and L33 features are high-specificity prediction channels. F30:6682 (48.63 proj) and F33:9048 (85.35 proj) lock in alanine. F33:326 (84.27 proj) supports asparagine as a polar alternative, but cannot overcome alanine's momentum from L28-31 MLP neurons.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model assembles a mixed hydrophobic-polar context with 6 structural contacts and minimal co-evolutionary signal. Early layers build a hydrophobic representation (leucine peaks at 32% at L9), but mid-layers shift toward polar character (serine rises to 36% at L24) as local polar residues are read. In the decision phase (L28-31), MLP neurons favor alanine as a small, flexible residue compatible with the mixed context, delivering a net 5.26 total_answer_proj at L28. The model underweights the charged character needed for glutamate, which receives strong support (N28:4082 with 0.697 proj, N29:4262 with 0.757 proj) but is systematically erased by opposing neurons (N30:362 with -1.024 proj, N31:4495 with -0.876 proj). The strongest evidence for alanine is the L28-31 MLP cascade, which interprets the ambiguous context as favoring flexibility over charge, leading to the incorrect prediction.
